 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c2a2><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mackeytl>MackeyTL</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#ff0000>(12/5/03 8:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=767.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Skald Report Feedback</span><hr size=1> &quot;&quot;1)        Maybe if you showed the progression of the shouts for each line they would better understand. I don’t think he realized that at 43 battle songs you end up with a level 20 ish for the second shout&quot;&quot;<br>
<br>
Let's take a close look at this. Remember that the two shouts are actually two separate lines for design purposes.<br>
<br>
1 - 2  Warcry  Enemy  0s/0s/15s  Rng: 700  7 dmg (Body)  2 power  <br>
2 - 7  Warholler  Enemy  0s/0s/15s  Rng: 700  21 dmg (Body)  5 power  <br>
3 - 18  Warshriek  Enemy  0s/0s/15s  Rng: 700  49 dmg (Body)  11 power  <br>
4 - 34  Warbellow  Enemy  0s/0s/15s  Rng: 700  89 dmg (Body)  21 power  <br>
5 - 43  War Howl  Enemy  0s/0s/15s  Rng: 700  111 dmg (Body)  27 power  <br>
<br>
<br>
1 - 4  Battle Whoop  Enemy  0s/0s/15s  Rng: 700  12 dmg (Body)  3 power  <br>
2 - 12  Battle Shout  Enemy  0s/0s/15s  Rng: 700  32 dmg (Body)  8 power  <br>
3 - 26  Battle Scream  Enemy  0s/0s/15s  Rng: 700  69 dmg (Body)  16 power  <br>
4 - 44  Battle Howl  Enemy  0s/0s/15s  Rng: 700  114 dmg (Body)  28 power  <br>
5 - 50  Battle Roar  Enemy  0s/0s/15s  Rng: 700  128 dmg (Body)  33 power  <br>
<br>
Warcry goes from 18 to 34(+16 levels).<br>
<br>
Battlecry goes from 26 to 44(+18 levels).<br>
<br>
The ways spells and spell levels are designed involves some fairly complicated formulas that we follow, and isn't just a case of us arbitrarily deciding whether a spell should be level 35 or level 36. <br>
<br>
Since things are always evolving, we don't look at templates when we design a spell or style line, since there's no telling when things might change again. Instead, we follow the established conventions and philosophies in place for design, which saves us the trouble of having to readjust every spell and style line anytime we make any single change. With the style review underway, there is no telling how the Skald weapon lines might pan out and what might be the &quot;threshhold style&quot; that people aim for.<br>
<br>
Hope that helps explain this issue a little more.<br>
<br>
-Mike<br>
<br>
Edit: Math edit.<br>
